          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "## Why the `prompt_id` is wrong\n\nThe bug is in the post-commit backfill condition. Here's the sequence:\n\n**1. Race when the second AI checkpoint is created** — `src/commands/checkpoint_agent/cursor_preset.rs:267-289` fetches the transcript from Cursor's global SQLite composer DB *at hook time*. Cursor doesn't atomically persist the triggering user bubble alongside the assistant turn — when the second AI edit fires the checkpoint hook, only message 1 (`b4c40ef9`) was in the DB. Message 2 (`5dd1410f`) hadn't landed yet.\n\n**2. Checkpoint stamps the wrong id** — `src/commands/checkpoint.rs:902` runs:\n\n```rust\ncheckpoint.user_prompt_id = latest_user_prompt_id(agent_run_result.as_ref());\n```\n\n`latest_user_prompt_id` (`checkpoint.rs:188-197`) reverse-iterates the in-hand transcript and returns the last `User` message id. With only message 1 visible, it returns `b4c40ef9`. The second checkpoint is persisted to the working log with this stale id.\n\n**3. Post-commit backfill refuses to fix it** — `src/authorship/post_commit.rs:722-736` is supposed to repair this exact race. It refetches the now-complete transcript (which has both user messages), builds a `user_msg_timeline`, then loops:\n\n```rust\nfor &idx in &indices {\n    if checkpoints[idx].user_prompt_id.is_none() {   // <-- the bug\n        let cp_ts = checkpoints[idx].timestamp;\n        checkpoints[idx].user_prompt_id = user_msg_timeline\n            .iter()\n            .filter(|(msg_ts, _)| *msg_ts == 0 || *msg_ts <= cp_ts)\n            .last()\n            .and_then(|(_, id)| id.clone());\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe `is_none()` guard only repairs checkpoints that have *no* prompt_id. A checkpoint whose id is already set — even to a stale value pointing at the *previous* user turn — is skipped. So the second checkpoint keeps `b4c40ef9` even though `cp_ts ≈ 1778138808` and message 2's ts ≈ `1778138800` would have matched the timeline filter.\n\nThe comment above the loop (\"checkpoints in a